gest real responses to this crisis. Could the drastic declines in housing markets have been avoided? Yes, if we reframe our housing values. Do you want to attract corporate investment to your town? You might want to think twice about doing so. The extinction of the “Celtic Tiger” may be charted in statistics, but the response in popular Irish mystery novels is much more compelling. China, while not immune to market vicissitudes, still booms, but at a considerable cost to its urban identities. Whether constructing a sustainable social framework for Mexican mega-cities or a neighborhood in London, these nine essays consider some strikingly similar strategies. And perhaps, as the contributors suggest, it’s time to look beyond the usual boundaries of urban, suburban, and exurban to forge new links among these communities that will benefit all citizens. Accessible to anyone with an interest in how cities cope today, Sustaining Cities presents a cautionary tale with a hopeful ending.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCities and townsxGrowth. 0aCity planningxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSociology, Urban. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbas, Ackbar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbbas, Ackbar.1 aAhrentzen, Sherry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhrentzen, Sherry.1 aIracheta, Alfonso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIracheta, Alfonso.1 aKincaid, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKincaid, Andrew.1 aKrause, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrause, Linda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMassood, Paula J.1 aMassood, Paula J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c